'''Pyrogenic flowering''' is the fire-stimulated [[flower]]ing  of plants in [[heathland]] and other fire-prone habitats. It is associated with species which have transient [[Soil seed bank|seed bank]]s, as opposed to [[canopy seed bank|canopy]] or persistent [[soil seed bank]]s. These species are mostly [[monocots]], but it is also observed in several species of woody [[dicot]]s.<ref name=Bradstock>{{cite book|author = Bradstock, Ross Andrew| title=Flammable Australia: the fire regimes and biodiversity of a continent|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4f8anIoS33MC&pg=PA216&lpg=PA216&dq=%22pyrogenic+flowering%22&source=bl&ots=kDhqI0u_qk&sig=e8opoxv-r5UpnpR4LallZpMeiD8&hl=en&ei=mtt5S4eBBoWSsgPBvvjLCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBoQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22pyrogenic%20flowering%22&f=false|publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2002|ISBN=0-521-80591-0|display-authors=etal}}</ref>

One of the most well known species to display this life cycle are those in the [[Waratah]] (Telopea) genus.<ref>[https://core.ac.uk/display/37026936 Seedling establishment in an pyrogenic flowering species: the role of time-since-fire, litter and post-dispersal seed predation By Andrew J Denham]</ref> With [[Telopea speciosissima]] being the [[floral emblem]] of the Australian state of [[New South Wales]].

